bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Actor, folk singer, and political activist Theodore Bikel was born in Vienna, Austria on May 2, 1924. In 1938, Nazi Germany invaded Austria and Bikel's family emigrated to British administered Palestine, where he lived on a kibbutz. Bikel got his start in acting at the Habimah Theater in Tel Aviv. He emigrated to Great Britain following World War II to study at the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art, performing several roles on the London stage in the 1940s. Bikel made his Broadway debut in Tonight in Samarkand in 1955, making the decision soon after to emigrate to the United States. In 1959, he originated the role of Baron von Trapp in the original Broadway production of The Sound of Music, opposite Mary Martin. His best-known stage role was that of "Tevye" in the musical Fiddler on the Roof, with more than 2000 performances over several decades. Bikel's film debut was in The African Queen (1951); he also appeared in The Defiant Ones (1956), My Fair Lady (1964), and The Russians Are Coming, the Russians are Coming (1966), among others. He was cast in numerous television roles during his career in both sitcoms and dramas. His stage, film, and television roles encompassed a wide variety of nationalities.

Bikel was also a folk singer, recording 37 albums for the Elektra label, and sang in over 20 languages, including Yiddish, Hebrew, Russian, German, and Spanish. He was a founder of the Newport Folk Festival and was involved with planning as well as performing at the annual event in the 1960s and early 1970s. He was active in the New York folk scene in the 1960s, living in Greenwich Village.

Bikel's activism and involvement in politics encompassed a variety of areas. He served as Vice President and President (1973-1982) of Actors' Equity Association (AEA) and as Vice President of the Federation Internationale des Acteurs (FIA); in addition, he was President of the AFL-CIO affiliated Associated Actors and Artistes of America ("Four A's") for over 25 years. In 1977, Bikel was appointed by President Jimmy Carter to serve a five-year term on the National Council for the Arts. Outside of the arts, Bikel was active in civil rights and anti-Apartheid causes and was a delegate to the 1968 Democratic National Convention in Chicago. He campaigned for New York City mayors John V. Lindsay and Edward Koch. Bikel was a long-time supporter of Israel and was especially active in Jewish causes; he served as Vice President of the American Jewish Congress (AJC) and was also interested in the welfare of Jews in the Soviet Union.
Bikel continued to perform and be politically active until shortly before his death. He died on July 21, 2015 in Los Angeles.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: This collection primarily consists of correspondence and subject files pertaining to Theodore Bikel's careers in music, stage, film, and television, as well as personal and family matters, and political and social activism. Also included are sheet music, scripts, and screenplays; clippings and ephemera; audiovisual material; awards; and a small amount of photographs.

arrangement.head: Organization and Arrangement
arrangement.p:
This collection has been arranged in the following series:
Series 1: Correspondence and subject files, 1946-2012
Subseries 1.1: Chronological files, 1946-2002
Subseries 1.2: Loose and hanging files, 1962-2012
Subseries 1.3: Actors' Equity Association subject files, 1960-1985
Subseries 1.4: Writings, circa 1960-1993, 2000s
Series 2: Musical arrangements, 1940s-2000s
Series 3: Scripts and screenplays, 1951-2014
Series 4: Photographs, 1950s-2006
Series 5: Memorabilia, 1944-2014
Series 6: Audiovisual material, 1957-2014

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Series primarily consists of chronological correspondence and subject files containing both professional and personal material.

For searching purposes, please note that Bikel used the British spelling of theatre and generally referred to Fiddler on the Roof simply as Fiddler. He also used numerous acronyms in his label titles; some of the more common ones are listed below.

list.item: ACA: American Council for the Arts

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: File titles in this series are usually those that appear on the original labels. As such, they may include abbreviations or misspellings applied by Bikel. Supplied titles are in parentheses.

did.langmaterial: The bulk of this material is in German.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Bikel's arrangement and labeling practices changed over time. There are some gaps in alphabetical sequences within certain years. File sets were likely pre-labeled so some folders are empty.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Correspondence files are usually divided into personal, business, and fan mail. Subject files pertain to Bikel's Elektra recording career, concert appearances, and the Newport Folk Festival; his acting career in general and specific stage, film, and television productions; business dealings, management, and investments; political activism and Bikel's involvement with various organizations, including the American Jewish Congress (AJC), Actors' Equity Association (AEA), National Endowment for the Arts (NEA), and others; and travel.

This subseries also contains correspondence from or items relating to Bikel family members, especially parents Josef and Miriam Bikel; see early correspondence in boxes 1, 2, 224, and 226, as well as files within individual years, usually labeled "Bikel" or "Family". The bulk of this material is in German.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Files are mostly in the order presumably kept by Bikel: generally chronological, then filed alphabetical by title within each year, usually with uniformly printed labels. Accordion and other large subject files that encompass several years are filed at the end of the appropriate decade.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Folders with the "various" label imply some sort of internal organization (e.g. a grouping of violin parts). Folders with the "miscellaneous" label imply no internal organization and honor the original foldering system.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: This series primarily consists of musical arrangements of Bikel's standard performance pieces along with lyrics, songbooks, album information, and publisher correspondence. Includes music from classical, musical theater, and Jewish, American, and Russian folk genres in English, German, Hebrew, Russian, Spanish, and Yiddish. This series also includes two 7-inch vinyl records and one audiocassette.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Files maintain their existing order which was presumably kept by Bikel.
